  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions. Specific legal definitions can vary between jurisdictions, but typically involve three key stages:\n\n1. Placement: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system\n2. Layering: Concealing the source of funds through multiple transactions\n3. Integration: Reintroducing the \"cleaned\" money into legitimate economic activities\n\nLegal definitions usually require:\n- Intentional concealment of illegal funds\n- Knowledge that money originates from criminal activity\n- Deliberate attempts to disguise the money's origin\n\nPrecise details depend on specific national and international laws like:\n- U.S. Bank Secrecy Act\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\nCommon elements include:\n- Transactions designed to hide illegal funds\n- Deliberately obscuring financial trails\n- Converting \"dirty\" money to seemingly legitimate assets\n\nThese are general legal principles. For specific legal advice, consulting a qualified attorney is recommended.",
